sketch:
In establishing the main theorem, the proof is said to be “analogous to the proof of hou2024restrictions, Theorem 1.2.” The paper proceeds by introducing “the integrated pretrace formula and its amplification” and using that “at finite split places, the unitary group considered is isomorphic to $\operatorname{GL}(3)$, which allows us to use the amplifier constructed in marshall2015restrictions, restrictions at those places.” After “showing a counting result,” the authors prove the main theorem next by assuming the following proposition.

\begin{proposition}\label{prop: bound for I}
    Suppose that $g\in G_0$ with $d(g,e)\leq1$, $\lambda^{\epsilon'}\leq\beta\leq\lambda^{1-\epsilon'}$ and $\phi \in \cS(\overline{\BD}\times\BR) $  satisfies $\|\phi \|_2 = 1$. 
    \begin{enumerate}[(1)]
        \item If $\supp(\sF_t\phi) \subset \overline{\BD}\times (\BR\backslash \pm[\lambda-\beta, \lambda+\beta])$, then we have
        \begin{align}\label{eq: bd for I(e)}
            I(\lambda,\phi,e)\ll_\epsilon \beta^{-1/2+\epsilon}.
        \end{align}
        \item Fix $\epsilon_0>0$. If $\supp(\sF_t\phi) \subset \overline{\BD}\times (\pm[\lambda-\beta,\lambda+\beta])$, and $g$ satisfies $d(g,MA)\geq \lambda^{-1/2+\epsilon_0}\beta^{1/2}$, then we have
        \begin{align}\label{eq: bd for I(g)}
            I(\lambda,\phi,g)\ll_{\epsilon_0,A} \lambda^{-A}.
        \end{align}
    \end{enumerate}
\end{proposition}

This proposition provides the estimates of the oscillatory integrals appearing in the geometric side of the amplified trace formula. The remainder of the paper is devoted to proving the proposition above.

